a Men, who joined the church as young women, offer evidence on how Russian Orthodoxy remained a viable, alternative presence in Soviet society, when all political, educational, and cultural institutions attempted to indoctrinate Soviet citizens with an atheistic perspective. Wallace L. Daniel's translation not only sheds light on Russia's religious and political history, but also shows how two educated women maintained their personal integrity in times when prevailing political and social headwinds moved in an opposite direction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aChristian martyrszSoviet UnionvBiography. 0aPersecutionzSoviet UnionxHistory. 4aMemoir. 4aReligious Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aRussian women in Stalin’s Russia, Russian Women in World War II, the Orthodox Church and Russian society, Saint Serafim of Sarov and Russian Saints and Martyrs, Catacomb Church.1 aDaniel, Wallace L.1 aDaniel, Wallace L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMen, Aleksandr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMen, Archpriest Aleksandr.1 aMen, Elena Semenovna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobson, Roy R.1 aRobson, Roy R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVasilevskaia, V. Ia., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVasilevskaia, Vera Iakovlevna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073908408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLET